      <hedline>
        <hl1>Busting Crime, or Just Eardrums?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Anne R Teicher of Neighborhood Coalition for Shelter points out that homeless people at center on East 77th Streetare likely to be considered intruders under security system on Upper East Side, Manhattan, block (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''On Unmean Street, Thumbs Will Work as Crime Busters,'' (front page, Sept. 13): It is notable that in all of the hoopla about the Safe-Block security system on East 77th Street, nobody mentioned the presence on that block of a 24-hour center for homeless men and women who, because of their appearance, are often perceived as intruders by their neighbors.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''On Unmean Street, Thumbs Will Work as Crime Busters,'' (front page, Sept. 13): It is notable that in all of the hoopla about the Safe-Block security system on East 77th Street, nobody mentioned the presence on that block of a 24-hour center for homeless men and women who, because of their appearance, are often perceived as intruders by their neighbors.</p>
        <p>It is unfortunate that we must now educate our clients about the potential danger of being targeted by this ''crime buster'' effort.</p>
        <p>ANNE R. TEICHER  Executive Director  Neighborhood Coalition for Shelter  New York, Sept. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
